      22             :  *    CAPITALS are used to represent terminal symbols.
      23             :  *    non-capitals are used to represent non-terminals.
      24             :  *
      25             :  *    In general, nothing in this file should initiate database accesses
      26             :  *    nor depend on changeable state (such as SET variables).  If you do
      27             :  *    database accesses, your code will fail when we have aborted the
      28             :  *    current transaction and are just parsing commands to find the next
      29             :  *    ROLLBACK or COMMIT.  If you make use of SET variables, then you
      30             :  *    will do the wrong thing in multi-query strings like this:
      31             :  *          SET constraint_exclusion TO off; SELECT * FROM foo;
      32             :  *    because the entire string is parsed by gram.y before the SET gets
      33             :  *    executed.  Anything that depends on the database or changeable state
      34             :  *    should be handled during parse analysis so that it happens at the
      35             :  *    right time not the wrong time.
      36             :  *
      37             :  * WARNINGS
      38             :  *    If you use a list, make sure the datum is a node so that the printing
      39             :  *    routines work.

      41             :  *    Sometimes we assign constants to makeStrings. Make sure we don't free
      42             :  *    those.
      43             :  *

      70             : /*
      71             :  * Location tracking support --- simpler than bison's default, since we only
      72             :  * want to track the start position not the end position of each nonterminal.
      73             :  */
      74             : #define YYLLOC_DEFAULT(Current, Rhs, N) \
      75             :     do { \
      76             :         if ((N) > 0) \
      77             :             (Current) = (Rhs)[1]; \
      78             :         else \
      79             :             (Current) = (-1); \
      80             :     } while (0)
      81             : 
      82             : /*
      83             :  * The above macro assigns -1 (unknown) as the parse location of any
      84             :  * nonterminal that was reduced from an empty rule, or whose leftmost
      85             :  * component was reduced from an empty rule.  This is problematic
      86             :  * for nonterminals defined like
      87             :  *      OptFooList: / * EMPTY * / { ... } | OptFooList Foo { ... } ;
      88             :  * because we'll set -1 as the location during the first reduction and then
      89             :  * copy it during each subsequent reduction, leaving us with -1 for the
      90             :  * location even when the list is not empty.  To fix that, do this in the
      91             :  * action for the nonempty rule(s):
      92             :  *      if (@$ < 0) @$ = @2;
      93             :  * (Although we have many nonterminals that follow this pattern, we only
      94             :  * bother with fixing @$ like this when the nonterminal's parse location
      95             :  * is actually referenced in some rule.)
      96             :  *
      97             :  * A cleaner answer would be to make YYLLOC_DEFAULT scan all the Rhs
      98             :  * locations until it's found one that's not -1.  Then we'd get a correct
      99             :  * location for any nonterminal that isn't entirely empty.  But this way
     100             :  * would add overhead to every rule reduction, and so far there's not been
     101             :  * a compelling reason to pay that overhead.
     102             :  */
     103             : 
     104             : /*
     105             :  * Bison doesn't allocate anything that needs to live across parser calls,
     106             :  * so we can easily have it use palloc instead of malloc.  This prevents
     107             :  * memory leaks if we error out during parsing.  Note this only works with
     108             :  * bison >= 2.0.  However, in bison 1.875 the default is to use alloca()
     109             :  * if possible, so there's not really much problem anyhow, at least if
     110             :  * you're building with gcc.
     111             :  */
     112             : #define YYMALLOC palloc
     113             : #define YYFREE   pfree
     114             :

     595             : 
     596             : /*
     597             :  * Non-keyword token types.  These are hard-wired into the "flex" lexer.
     598             :  * They must be listed first so that their numeric codes do not depend on
     599             :  * the set of keywords.  PL/pgSQL depends on this so that it can share the
     600             :  * same lexer.  If you add/change tokens here, fix PL/pgSQL to match!
     601             :  *
     602             :  * DOT_DOT is unused in the core SQL grammar, and so will always provoke
     603             :  * parse errors.  It is needed by PL/pgSQL.
     604             :  */
     605             : %token <str>  IDENT FCONST SCONST BCONST XCONST Op
     606             : %token <ival> ICONST PARAM
     607             : %token          TYPECAST DOT_DOT COLON_EQUALS EQUALS_GREATER
     608             : %token          LESS_EQUALS GREATER_EQUALS NOT_EQUALS
     609             : 
     610             : /*
     611             :  * If you want to make any keyword changes, update the keyword table in
     612             :  * src/include/parser/kwlist.h and add new keywords to the appropriate one
     613             :  * of the reserved-or-not-so-reserved keyword lists, below; search
     614             :  * this file for "Keyword category lists".

     702             : 
     703             :     XML_P XMLATTRIBUTES XMLCONCAT XMLELEMENT XMLEXISTS XMLFOREST XMLNAMESPACES

     705             : 
     706             :     YEAR_P YES_P
     707             : 
     708             :     ZONE
     709             : 
     710             : /*
     711             :  * The grammar thinks these are keywords, but they are not in the kwlist.h
     712             :  * list and so can never be entered directly.  The filter in parser.c
     713             :  * creates these tokens when required (based on looking one token ahead).
     714             :  *
     715             :  * NOT_LA exists so that productions such as NOT LIKE can be given the same
     716             :  * precedence as LIKE; otherwise they'd effectively have the same precedence
     717             :  * as NOT, at least with respect to their left-hand subexpression.
     718             :  * NULLS_LA and WITH_LA are needed to make the grammar LALR(1).
     719             :  */
     720             : %token      NOT_LA NULLS_LA WITH_LA
     721             : 
     722             : 
     723             : /* Precedence: lowest to highest */
     724             : %nonassoc   SET             /* see relation_expr_opt_alias */
     725             : %left       UNION EXCEPT
     726             : %left       INTERSECT
     727             : %left       OR
     728             : %left       AND
     729             : %right      NOT
     730             : %nonassoc   IS ISNULL NOTNULL   /* IS sets precedence for IS NULL, etc */
     731             : %nonassoc   '<' '>' '=' LESS_EQUALS GREATER_EQUALS NOT_EQUALS
     732             : %nonassoc   BETWEEN IN_P LIKE ILIKE SIMILAR NOT_LA
     733             : %nonassoc   ESCAPE          /* ESCAPE must be just above LIKE/ILIKE/SIMILAR */
     734             : %left       POSTFIXOP       /* dummy for postfix Op rules */
     735             : /*
     736             :  * To support target_el without AS, we must give IDENT an explicit priority
     737             :  * between POSTFIXOP and Op.  We can safely assign the same priority to
     738             :  * various unreserved keywords as needed to resolve ambiguities (this can't
     739             :  * have any bad effects since obviously the keywords will still behave the
     740             :  * same as if they weren't keywords).  We need to do this:
     741             :  * for PARTITION, RANGE, ROWS, GROUPS to support opt_existing_window_name;
     742             :  * for RANGE, ROWS, GROUPS so that they can follow a_expr without creating
     743             :  * postfix-operator problems;
     744             :  * for GENERATED so that it can follow b_expr;
     745             :  * and for NULL so that it can follow b_expr in ColQualList without creating
     746             :  * postfix-operator problems.
     747             :  *
     748             :  * To support CUBE and ROLLUP in GROUP BY without reserving them, we give them
     749             :  * an explicit priority lower than '(', so that a rule with CUBE '(' will shift
     750             :  * rather than reducing a conflicting rule that takes CUBE as a function name.
     751             :  * Using the same precedence as IDENT seems right for the reasons given above.
     752             :  *
     753             :  * The frame_bound productions UNBOUNDED PRECEDING and UNBOUNDED FOLLOWING
     754             :  * are even messier: since UNBOUNDED is an unreserved keyword (per spec!),
     755             :  * there is no principled way to distinguish these from the productions
     756             :  * a_expr PRECEDING/FOLLOWING.  We hack this up by giving UNBOUNDED slightly
     757             :  * lower precedence than PRECEDING and FOLLOWING.  At present this doesn't
     758             :  * appear to cause UNBOUNDED to be treated differently from other unreserved
     759             :  * keywords anywhere else in the grammar, but it's definitely risky.  We can
     760             :  * blame any funny behavior of UNBOUNDED on the SQL standard, though.
     761             :  */
     762             : %nonassoc   UNBOUNDED       /* ideally should have same precedence as IDENT */
     763             : %nonassoc   IDENT GENERATED NULL_P PARTITION RANGE ROWS GROUPS PRECEDING FOLLOWING CUBE ROLLUP
     764             : %left       Op OPERATOR     /* multi-character ops and user-defined operators */
     765             : %left       '+' '-'
     766             : %left       '*' '/' '%'
     767             : %left       '^'
     768             : /* Unary Operators */
     769             : %left       AT              /* sets precedence for AT TIME ZONE */
     770             : %left       COLLATE
     771             : %right      UMINUS
     772             : %left       '[' ']'
     773             : %left       '(' ')'
     774             : %left       TYPECAST
     775             : %left       '.'
     776             : /*
     777             :  * These might seem to be low-precedence, but actually they are not part
     778             :  * of the arithmetic hierarchy at all in their use as JOIN operators.
     779             :  * We make them high-precedence to support their use as function names.
     780             :  * They wouldn't be given a precedence at all, were it not that we need
     781             :  * left-associativity among the JOIN rules themselves.
     782             :  */
     783             : %left       JOIN CROSS LEFT FULL RIGHT INNER_P NATURAL
     784             : /* kluge to keep xml_whitespace_option from causing shift/reduce conflicts */
     785             : %right      PRESERVE STRIP_P
     786             : 
     787             : %%
     788             : 
     789             : /*
     790             :  *  The target production for the whole parse.
     791             :  */
     792             : stmtblock:  stmtmulti
     793             :             {
     794       99442 :                 pg_yyget_extra(yyscanner)->parsetree = $1;
     795             :             }
     796             :         ;
     797             : 
     798             : /*
     799             :  * At top level, we wrap each stmt with a RawStmt node carrying start location
     800             :  * and length of the stmt's text.  Notice that the start loc/len are driven
     801             :  * entirely from semicolon locations (@2).  It would seem natural to use
     802             :  * @1 or @3 to get the true start location of a stmt, but that doesn't work
     803             :  * for statements that can start with empty nonterminals (opt_with_clause is
     804             :  * the main offender here); as noted in the comments for YYLLOC_DEFAULT,
     805             :  * we'd get -1 for the location in such cases.
     806             :  * We also take care to discard empty statements entirely.
     807             :  */
     808             : stmtmulti:  stmtmulti ';' stmt
     809             :                 {
     810       74738 :                     if ($1 != NIL)
     811             :                     {
     812             :                         /* update length of previous stmt */
     813       74728 :                         updateRawStmtEnd(llast_node(RawStmt, $1), @2);
     814             :                     }
     815       74738 :                     if ($3 != NULL)
     816         358 :                         $$ = lappend($1, makeRawStmt($3, @2 + 1));
     817             :                     else
     818       74380 :                         $$ = $1;
     819             :                 }
     820             :             | stmt
     821             :                 {
     822       99442 :                     if ($1 != NULL)
     823       99428 :                         $$ = list_make1(makeRawStmt($1, 0));
     824             :                     else
     825          14 :                         $$ = NIL;
     826             :                 }
     827             :         ;

    3422             : /* DEFAULT NULL is already the default for Postgres.

    3427             :  * WITH NULL and NULL are not SQL-standard syntax elements,
    3428             :  * so leave them out. Use DEFAULT NULL to explicitly indicate
    3429             :  * that a column may have that value. WITH NULL leads to
    3430             :  * shift/reduce conflicts with WITH TIME ZONE anyway.

    3433             :  * DEFAULT expression must be b_expr not a_expr to prevent shift/reduce

    6978             : 
    6979             : /*
    6980             :  * Privilege names are represented as strings; the validity of the privilege
    6981             :  * names gets checked at execution.  This is a bit annoying but we have little
    6982             :  * choice because of the syntactic conflict with lists of role names in
    6983             :  * GRANT/REVOKE.  What's more, we have to call out in the "privilege"
    6984             :  * production any reserved keywords that need to be usable as privilege names.
    6985             :  */
    6986             : 
    6987             : /* either ALL [PRIVILEGES] or a list of individual privileges */
    6988             : privileges: privilege_list

    7797             : 
    7798             : /*
    7799             :  * The SQL standard offers no guidance on how to declare aggregate argument
    7800             :  * lists, since it doesn't have CREATE AGGREGATE etc.  We accept these cases:
    7801             :  *
    7802             :  * (*)                                  - normal agg with no args
    7803             :  * (aggr_arg,...)                       - normal agg with args
    7804             :  * (ORDER BY aggr_arg,...)              - ordered-set agg with no direct args
    7805             :  * (aggr_arg,... ORDER BY aggr_arg,...) - ordered-set agg with direct args
    7806             :  *
    7807             :  * The zero-argument case is spelled with '*' for consistency with COUNT(*).
    7808             :  *
    7809             :  * An additional restriction is that if the direct-args list ends in a
    7810             :  * VARIADIC item, the ordered-args list must contain exactly one item that
    7811             :  * is also VARIADIC with the same type.  This allows us to collapse the two
    7812             :  * VARIADIC items into one, which is necessary to represent the aggregate in
    7813             :  * pg_proc.  We check this at the grammar stage so that we can return a list
    7814             :  * in which the second VARIADIC item is already discarded, avoiding extra work
    7815             :  * in cases such as DROP AGGREGATE.
    7816             :  *
    7817             :  * The return value of this production is a two-element list, in which the
    7818             :  * first item is a sublist of FunctionParameter nodes (with any duplicate
    7819             :  * VARIADIC item already dropped, as per above) and the second is an integer
    7820             :  * Value node, containing -1 if there was no ORDER BY and otherwise the number
    7821             :  * of argument declarations before the ORDER BY.  (If this number is equal
    7822             :  * to the first sublist's length, then we dropped a duplicate VARIADIC item.)
    7823             :  * This representation is passed as-is to CREATE AGGREGATE; for operations
    7824             :  * on existing aggregates, we can just apply extractArgTypes to the first
    7825             :  * sublist.
    7826             :  */
    7827             : aggr_args:  '(' '*' ')'
    7828             :                 {
    7829          34 :                     $$ = list_make2(NIL, makeInteger(-1));
    7830             :                 }
    7831             :             | '(' aggr_args_list ')'
    7832             :                 {
    7833         162 :                     $$ = list_make2($2, makeInteger(-1));
    7834             :                 }
    7835             :             | '(' ORDER BY aggr_args_list ')'
    7836             :                 {
    7837           2 :                     $$ = list_make2($4, makeInteger(0));
    7838             :                 }
    7839             :             | '(' aggr_args_list ORDER BY aggr_args_list ')'
    7840             :                 {

   11258             : /*****************************************************************************
   11259             :  *
   11260             :  *      QUERY:
   11261             :  *              SELECT STATEMENTS
   11262             :  *
   11263             :  *****************************************************************************/
   11264             : 
   11265             : /* A complete SELECT statement looks like this.
   11266             :  *
   11267             :  * The rule returns either a single SelectStmt node or a tree of them,
   11268             :  * representing a set-operation tree.
   11269             :  *
   11270             :  * There is an ambiguity when a sub-SELECT is within an a_expr and there
   11271             :  * are excess parentheses: do the parentheses belong to the sub-SELECT or
   11272             :  * to the surrounding a_expr?  We don't really care, but bison wants to know.
   11273             :  * To resolve the ambiguity, we are careful to define the grammar so that
   11274             :  * the decision is staved off as long as possible: as long as we can keep
   11275             :  * absorbing parentheses into the sub-SELECT, we will do so, and only when
   11276             :  * it's no longer possible to do that will we decide that parens belong to
   11277             :  * the expression.  For example, in "SELECT (((SELECT 2)) + 3)" the extra
   11278             :  * parentheses are treated as part of the sub-select.  The necessity of doing
   11279             :  * it that way is shown by "SELECT (((SELECT 2)) UNION SELECT 2)".    Had we
   11280             :  * parsed "((SELECT 2))" as an a_expr, it'd be too late to go back to the
   11281             :  * SELECT viewpoint when we see the UNION.
   11282             :  *
   11283             :  * This approach is implemented by defining a nonterminal select_with_parens,
   11284             :  * which represents a SELECT with at least one outer layer of parentheses,
   11285             :  * and being careful to use select_with_parens, never '(' SelectStmt ')',
   11286             :  * in the expression grammar.  We will then have shift-reduce conflicts
   11287             :  * which we can resolve in favor of always treating '(' <select> ')' as
   11288             :  * a select_with_parens.  To resolve the conflicts, the productions that
   11289             :  * conflict with the select_with_parens productions are manually given
   11290             :  * precedences lower than the precedence of ')', thereby ensuring that we
   11291             :  * shift ')' (and then reduce to select_with_parens) rather than trying to
   11292             :  * reduce the inner <select> nonterminal to something else.  We use UMINUS
   11293             :  * precedence for this, which is a fairly arbitrary choice.
   11294             :  *
   11295             :  * To be able to define select_with_parens itself without ambiguity, we need
   11296             :  * a nonterminal select_no_parens that represents a SELECT structure with no
   11297             :  * outermost parentheses.  This is a little bit tedious, but it works.
   11298             :  *
   11299             :  * In non-expression contexts, we use SelectStmt which can represent a SELECT
   11300             :  * with or without outer parentheses.
   11301             :  */
   11302             : 
   11303             : SelectStmt: select_no_parens            %prec UMINUS
   11304             :             | select_with_parens        %prec UMINUS
   11305             :         ;
   11306             : 
   11307             : select_with_parens:
   11308        9662 :             '(' select_no_parens ')'                { $$ = $2; }
   11309          44 :             | '(' select_with_parens ')'            { $$ = $2; }
   11310             :         ;
   11311             : 
   11312             : /*
   11313             :  * This rule parses the equivalent of the standard's <query expression>.
   11314             :  * The duplicative productions are annoying, but hard to get rid of without
   11315             :  * creating shift/reduce conflicts.
   11316             :  *
   11317             :  *  The locking clause (FOR UPDATE etc) may be before or after LIMIT/OFFSET.
   11318             :  *  In <=7.2.X, LIMIT/OFFSET had to be after FOR UPDATE
   11319             :  *  We now support both orderings, but prefer LIMIT/OFFSET before the locking
   11320             :  * clause.
   11321             :  *  2002-08-28 bjm
   11322             :  */
   11323             : select_no_parens:
   11324       66022 :             simple_select                       { $$ = $1; }
   11325             :             | select_clause sort_clause
   11326             :                 {
   11327        9082 :                     insertSelectOptions((SelectStmt *) $1, $2, NIL,
   11328             :                                         NULL, NULL, NULL,
   11329             :                                         yyscanner);
   11330        9082 :                     $$ = $1;
   11331             :                 }
   11332             :             | select_clause opt_sort_clause for_locking_clause opt_select_limit
   11333             :                 {
   11334         440 :                     insertSelectOptions((SelectStmt *) $1, $2, $3,
   11335         440 :                                         list_nth($4, 0), list_nth($4, 1),
   11336             :                                         NULL,
   11337             :                                         yyscanner);
   11338         440 :                     $$ = $1;
   11339             :                 }
   11340             :             | select_clause opt_sort_clause select_limit opt_for_locking_clause
   11341             :                 {
   11342         566 :                     insertSelectOptions((SelectStmt *) $1, $2, $4,
   11343         566 :                                         list_nth($3, 0), list_nth($3, 1),
   11344             :                                         NULL,
   11345             :                                         yyscanner);
   11346         566 :                     $$ = $1;
   11347             :                 }
   11348             :             | with_clause select_clause
   11349             :                 {
   11350         286 :                     insertSelectOptions((SelectStmt *) $2, NULL, NIL,
   11351             :                                         NULL, NULL,
   11352         286 :                                         $1,
   11353             :                                         yyscanner);
   11354         286 :                     $$ = $2;
   11355             :                 }
   11356             :             | with_clause select_clause sort_clause
   11357             :                 {
   11358          36 :                     insertSelectOptions((SelectStmt *) $2, $3, NIL,
   11359             :                                         NULL, NULL,
   11360          36 :                                         $1,
   11361             :                                         yyscanner);
   11362          36 :                     $$ = $2;
   11363             :                 }
   11364             :             | with_clause select_clause opt_sort_clause for_locking_clause opt_select_limit
   11365             :                 {
   11366           4 :                     insertSelectOptions((SelectStmt *) $2, $3, $4,
   11367           2 :                                         list_nth($5, 0), list_nth($5, 1),
   11368           2 :                                         $1,
   11369             :                                         yyscanner);
   11370           2 :                     $$ = $2;
   11371             :                 }
   11372             :             | with_clause select_clause opt_sort_clause select_limit opt_for_locking_clause
   11373             :                 {
   11374          24 :                     insertSelectOptions((SelectStmt *) $2, $3, $5,
   11375          12 :                                         list_nth($4, 0), list_nth($4, 1),
   11376          12 :                                         $1,
   11377             :                                         yyscanner);
   11378          12 :                     $$ = $2;
   11379             :                 }
   11380             :         ;
   11381             : 
   11382             : select_clause:
   11383       16734 :             simple_select                           { $$ = $1; }
   11384         102 :             | select_with_parens                    { $$ = $1; }
   11385             :         ;
   11386             : 
   11387             : /*
   11388             :  * This rule parses SELECT statements that can appear within set operations,
   11389             :  * including UNION, INTERSECT and EXCEPT.  '(' and ')' can be used to specify
   11390             :  * the ordering of the set operations.  Without '(' and ')' we want the
   11391             :  * operations to be ordered per the precedence specs at the head of this file.
   11392             :  *
   11393             :  * As with select_no_parens, simple_select cannot have outer parentheses,
   11394             :  * but can have parenthesized subclauses.
   11395             :  *
   11396             :  * Note that sort clauses cannot be included at this level --- SQL requires
   11397             :  *      SELECT foo UNION SELECT bar ORDER BY baz
   11398             :  * to be parsed as
   11399             :  *      (SELECT foo UNION SELECT bar) ORDER BY baz
   11400             :  * not
   11401             :  *      SELECT foo UNION (SELECT bar ORDER BY baz)
   11402             :  * Likewise for WITH, FOR UPDATE and LIMIT.  Therefore, those clauses are
   11403             :  * described as part of the select_no_parens production, not simple_select.
   11404             :  * This does not limit functionality, because you can reintroduce these
   11405             :  * clauses inside parentheses.
   11406             :  *
   11407             :  * NOTE: only the leftmost component SelectStmt should have INTO.
   11408             :  * However, this is not checked by the grammar; parse analysis must check it.
   11409             :  */
   11410             : simple_select:

   12035             : 
   12036             : /*
   12037             :  * It may seem silly to separate joined_table from table_ref, but there is
   12038             :  * method in SQL's madness: if you don't do it this way you get reduce-
   12039             :  * reduce conflicts, because it's not clear to the parser generator whether
   12040             :  * to expect alias_clause after ')' or not.  For the same reason we must
   12041             :  * treat 'JOIN' and 'join_type JOIN' separately, rather than allowing
   12042             :  * join_type to expand to empty; if we try it, the parser generator can't
   12043             :  * figure out when to reduce an empty join_type right after table_ref.
   12044             :  *
   12045             :  * Note that a CROSS JOIN is the same as an unqualified
   12046             :  * INNER JOIN, and an INNER JOIN/ON has the same shape
   12047             :  * but a qualification expression to limit membership.

   12049             :  * tables and the shape is determined by which columns are

   12563             : /*****************************************************************************
   12564             :  *
   12565             :  *  Type syntax
   12566             :  *      SQL introduces a large amount of type-specific syntax.
   12567             :  *      Define individual clauses to handle these cases, and use

   13022             : /*****************************************************************************
   13023             :  *
   13024             :  *  expression grammar
   13025             :  *
   13026             :  *****************************************************************************/
   13027             : 
   13028             : /*
   13029             :  * General expressions
   13030             :  * This is the heart of the expression syntax.
   13031             :  *
   13032             :  * We have two expression types: a_expr is the unrestricted kind, and
   13033             :  * b_expr is a subset that must be used in some places to avoid shift/reduce
   13034             :  * conflicts.  For example, we can't do BETWEEN as "BETWEEN a_expr AND a_expr"
   13035             :  * because that use of AND conflicts with AND as a boolean operator.  So,
   13036             :  * b_expr is used in BETWEEN and we remove boolean keywords from b_expr.
   13037             :  *
   13038             :  * Note that '(' a_expr ')' is a b_expr, so an unrestricted expression can
   13039             :  * always be used by surrounding it with parens.
   13040             :  *
   13041             :  * c_expr is all the productions that are common to a_expr and b_expr;
   13042             :  * it's factored out just to eliminate redundant coding.
   13043             :  *
   13044             :  * Be careful of productions involving more than one terminal token.
   13045             :  * By default, bison will assign such productions the precedence of their
   13046             :  * last terminal, but in nearly all cases you want it to be the precedence
   13047             :  * of the first terminal instead; otherwise you will not get the behavior
   13048             :  * you expect!  So we use %prec annotations freely to set precedences.
   13049             :  */
   13050      396062 : a_expr:     c_expr                                  { $$ = $1; }
   13051             :             | a_expr TYPECAST Typename
   13052       24388 :                     { $$ = makeTypeCast($1, $3, @2); }
   13053             :             | a_expr COLLATE any_name
   13054             :                 {
   13055        1296 :                     CollateClause *n = makeNode(CollateClause);
   13056        1296 :                     n->arg = $1;
   13057        1296 :                     n->collname = $3;
   13058        1296 :                     n->location = @2;
   13059        1296 :                     $$ = (Node *) n;
   13060             :                 }
   13061             :             | a_expr AT TIME ZONE a_expr            %prec AT
   13062             :                 {
   13063         240 :                     $$ = (Node *) makeFuncCall(SystemFuncName("timezone"),
   13064         120 :                                                list_make2($5, $1),
   13065         120 :                                                @2);
   13066             :                 }
   13067             :         /*
   13068             :          * These operators must be called out explicitly in order to make use
   13069             :          * of bison's automatic operator-precedence handling.  All other
   13070             :          * operator names are handled by the generic productions using "Op",
   13071             :          * below; and all those operators will have the same precedence.
   13072             :          *
   13073             :          * If you add more explicitly-known operators, be sure to add them
   13074             :          * also to b_expr and to the MathOp list below.
   13075             :          */
   13076             :             | '+' a_expr                    %prec UMINUS
   13077           4 :                 { $$ = (Node *) makeSimpleA_Expr(AEXPR_OP, "+", NULL, $2, @1); }
   13078             :             | '-' a_expr                    %prec UMINUS
   13079        1344 :                 { $$ = doNegate($2, @1); }
   13080             :             | a_expr '+' a_expr
   13081        2144 :                 { $$ = (Node *) makeSimpleA_Expr(AEXPR_OP, "+", $1, $3, @2); }
   13082             :             | a_expr '-' a_expr
   13083        1602 :                 { $$ = (Node *) makeSimpleA_Expr(AEXPR_OP, "-", $1, $3, @2); }
   13084             :             | a_expr '*' a_expr
   13085         812 :                 { $$ = (Node *) makeSimpleA_Expr(AEXPR_OP, "*", $1, $3, @2); }
   13086             :             | a_expr '/' a_expr
   13087         564 :                 { $$ = (Node *) makeSimpleA_Expr(AEXPR_OP, "/", $1, $3, @2); }
   13088             :             | a_expr '%' a_expr
   13089         224 :                 { $$ = (Node *) makeSimpleA_Expr(AEXPR_OP, "%", $1, $3, @2); }
   13090             :             | a_expr '^' a_expr
   13091          94 :                 { $$ = (Node *) makeSimpleA_Expr(AEXPR_OP, "^", $1, $3, @2); }
   13092             :             | a_expr '<' a_expr
   13093        2270 :                 { $$ = (Node *) makeSimpleA_Expr(AEXPR_OP, "<", $1, $3, @2); }
   13094             :             | a_expr '>' a_expr

   15035             :                                             "none"),
   15036             :                                      parser_errposition(@1)));
   15037             :                         }
   15038             :                         else
   15039             :                         {
   15040        1524 :                             n = makeRoleSpec(ROLESPEC_CSTRING, @1);
   15041        1524 :                             n->rolename = pstrdup($1);
   15042             :                         }
   15043        1906 :                         $$ = n;
   15044             :                     }
   15045             :             | CURRENT_USER
   15046             :                     {
   15047          42 :                         $$ = makeRoleSpec(ROLESPEC_CURRENT_USER, @1);
   15048             :                     }

   15051           0 :                         $$ = makeRoleSpec(ROLESPEC_SESSION_USER, @1);

   15054             : 
   15055             : role_list:  RoleSpec
   15056         462 :                     { $$ = list_make1($1); }
   15057             :             | role_list ',' RoleSpec
   15058          32 :                     { $$ = lappend($1, $3); }
   15059             :         ;
   15060             : 
   15061             : /*
   15062             :  * Name classification hierarchy.
   15063             :  *
   15064             :  * IDENT is the lexeme returned by the lexer for identifiers that match
   15065             :  * no known keyword.  In most cases, we can accept certain keywords as
   15066             :  * names, not only IDENTs.  We prefer to accept as many such keywords
   15067             :  * as possible to minimize the impact of "reserved words" on programmers.
   15068             :  * So, we divide names into several possible classes.  The classification
   15069             :  * is chosen in part to make keywords acceptable as names wherever possible.
   15070             :  */
   15071             : 
   15072             : /* Column identifier --- names that can be column, table, etc names.
   15073             :  */
   15074      356536 : ColId:      IDENT                                   { $$ = $1; }
   15075        4162 :             | unreserved_keyword                    { $$ = pstrdup($1); }
   15076         166 :             | col_name_keyword                      { $$ = pstrdup($1); }
   15077             :         ;
   15078             : 
   15079             : /* Type/function identifier --- names that can be type or function names.
   15080             :  */
   15081       63918 : type_function_name: IDENT                           { $$ = $1; }
   15082        7404 :             | unreserved_keyword                    { $$ = pstrdup($1); }
   15083           6 :             | type_func_name_keyword                { $$ = pstrdup($1); }
   15084             :         ;
   15085             : 
   15086             : /* Any not-fully-reserved word --- these names can be, eg, role names.
   15087             :  */
   15088        6616 : NonReservedWord:    IDENT                           { $$ = $1; }
   15089        3468 :             | unreserved_keyword                    { $$ = pstrdup($1); }
   15090           0 :             | col_name_keyword                      { $$ = pstrdup($1); }
   15091         294 :             | type_func_name_keyword                { $$ = pstrdup($1); }
   15092             :         ;
   15093             : 
   15094             : /* Column label --- allowed labels in "AS" clauses.
   15095             :  * This presently includes *all* Postgres keywords.
   15096             :  */

   15099          44 :             | col_name_keyword                      { $$ = pstrdup($1); }
   15100          50 :             | type_func_name_keyword                { $$ = pstrdup($1); }

   15102             :         ;
   15103             : 
   15104             : 
   15105             : /*
   15106             :  * Keyword category lists.  Generally, every keyword present in
   15107             :  * the Postgres grammar should appear in exactly one of these lists.
   15108             :  *
   15109             :  * Put a new keyword into the first list that it can go into without causing
   15110             :  * shift or reduce conflicts.  The earlier lists define "less reserved"
   15111             :  * categories of keywords.
   15112             :  *
   15113             :  * Make sure that each keyword's category in kwlist.h matches where
